            5.0 out of 5 stars
            
                Great Quality!!!
            
            
            
                
                    
                        Reviewed in the United States on March 7, 2018
                    
                    
                
            
        
        
            I'm on my second pair now. I am a budding musician and part of what I do is singing so when I need to learn vocals for a song I need to be able to properly hear the vocals. These headphones let me do just that. They pick up soaring high notes and deep bass-y notes without putting too much emphasis on one or the other and without getting tinny with higher frequencies. The only reason my last pair wore is because the cord developed a short near the tip due to excessive movement (before that I had left them in one place, left them plugged in, and hung them on a hook when not in use and they lasted for well over a year). I love these headphones!Edit: Quick update, two years later and these headphones are still going strong! They really are great for the price. The bass notes come through clear without overpowering the music and the high notes are clear as well without being tinny. Where these headphones really shine is for music that puts emphasis on vocals or for listening to podcasts as the mids are extremely clear. These are also comfortable to wear for long periods of time due to the plush padding on the ear cups. Still highly recommended and still loving these headphones!Edit 2: It's now been 4 years and these headphones are still going strong! Still no complaints, except that they seem to be discontinuing this model (the MH320s)! I'll be sure to take care and look after mine as I'm still loving the quality.

Please try again later.Bill Ruys4.0 out of 5 stars A good step up from the previous model Reviewed in the United States on October 7, 2014Style: 45mm with Leather EarpadsVerified Purchase After the discontinuation of the CAD MH310, of which I own 3 pairs, I was interested to hear what the CAD MH320 would bring to the table. The 310 were loosely based on a classic AKG design, whereas the 320 are more reminiscent of newer Audio Technica headphones. Although the two sets of headphones have similar model numbers, the new MH320 couldn't be physically more different than the former MH310.The newer MH320 phones sit slightly looser on my head, making them more comfortable. They are light and unobtrusive - much more so than the more bulky former model. The earcups are a little smaller than the previous model, so if you have large ears, they may not be such a great fit for you, but they are just big enough to cover my ears and no bigger. Unlike the MH310, which had a long straight cable, much of the cable on the new MH320 phones is coiled. Personally I have never been a fan of coiled cables, as they tend to tangle and give less length, but at this early stage, the cable has yet to cause me any consternation.The sound? Well, having spent a few hours with the new headphones and comparing them to the 310, the 320 are an improvement. For me, the MH310 was a little too bright in the high mids, which had a tendancy to make vocalists sound over-sibilent and cymbals and other high frequency sounds a little aggressive and fatiguing. The MH320 phones are much more subdued in that range. They don't sound dull by any means, but when you A/B them with the prior model, you realise how over-done the upper mids and highs were in the MH310. In the lower frequencies, the newer MH320 model matches the prodigious bass responce of the former model - no problems there. I feel I could comfortably listen to these headphones for many hours without ear fatigue. They sound full and very good for a set of closed back headphones. I feel they offer slightly less sound isolation from ambient noise than the previous model, but in every other respect, they are an acoustic upgrade.As a good quality pair of budget headphones for tracking and some mixing duties, I would certainly these headphones. Please try again later.Bill Ruys4.0 out of 5 stars A good step up from the previous model Reviewed in the United States on October 7, 2014Style: 45mm with Leather EarpadsVerified Purchase After the discontinuation of the CAD MH310, of which I own 3 pairs, I was interested to hear what the CAD MH320 would bring to the table. The 310 were loosely based on a classic AKG design, whereas the 320 are more reminiscent of newer Audio Technica headphones. Although the two sets of headphones have similar model numbers, the new MH320 couldn't be physically more different than the former MH310.The newer MH320 phones sit slightly looser on my head, making them more comfortable. They are light and unobtrusive - much more so than the more bulky former model. The earcups are a little smaller than the previous model, so if you have large ears, they may not be such a great fit for you, but they are just big enough to cover my ears and no bigger. Unlike the MH310, which had a long straight cable, much of the cable on the new MH320 phones is coiled. Personally I have never been a fan of coiled cables, as they tend to tangle and give less length, but at this early stage, the cable has yet to cause me any consternation.The sound? Well, having spent a few hours with the new headphones and comparing them to the 310, the 320 are an improvement. For me, the MH310 was a little too bright in the high mids, which had a tendancy to make vocalists sound over-sibilent and cymbals and other high frequency sounds a little aggressive and fatiguing. The MH320 phones are much more subdued in that range. They don't sound dull by any means, but when you A/B them with the prior model, you realise how over-done the upper mids and highs were in the MH310. In the lower frequencies, the newer MH320 model matches the prodigious bass responce of the former model - no problems there. I feel I could comfortably listen to these headphones for many hours without ear fatigue. They sound full and very good for a set of closed back headphones. I feel they offer slightly less sound isolation from ambient noise than the previous model, but in every other respect, they are an acoustic upgrade.As a good quality pair of budget headphones for tracking and some mixing duties, I would certainly these headphones. Bill Ruys4.0 out of 5 stars A good step up from the previous model Reviewed in the United States on October 7, 2014Style: 45mm with Leather EarpadsVerified Purchase After the discontinuation of the CAD MH310, of which I own 3 pairs, I was interested to hear what the CAD MH320 would bring to the table. Bill Ruys4.0 out of 5 stars A good step up from the previous model Reviewed in the United States on October 7, 2014Style: 45mm with Leather EarpadsVerified Purchase After the discontinuation of the CAD MH310, of which I own 3 pairs, I was interested to hear what the CAD MH320 would bring to the table. The 310 were loosely based on a classic AKG design, whereas the 320 are more reminiscent of newer Audio Technica headphones. Although the two sets of headphones have similar model numbers, the new MH320 couldn't be physically more different than the former MH310.The newer MH320 phones sit slightly looser on my head, making them more comfortable. They are light and unobtrusive - much more so than the more bulky former model. The earcups are a little smaller than the previous model, so if you have large ears, they may not be such a great fit for you, but they are just big enough to cover my ears and no bigger. Unlike the MH310, which had a long straight cable, much of the cable on the new MH320 phones is coiled. Personally I have never been a fan of coiled cables, as they tend to tangle and give less length, but at this early stage, the cable has yet to cause me any consternation.The sound? Well, having spent a few hours with the new headphones and comparing them to the 310, the 320 are an improvement. In the lower frequencies, the newer MH320 model matches the prodigious bass responce of the former model - no problems there. I feel I could comfortably listen to these headphones for many hours without ear fatigue. They sound full and very good for a set of closed back headphones. I feel they offer slightly less sound isolation from ambient noise than the previous model, but in every other respect, they are an acoustic upgrade.As a good quality pair of budget headphones for tracking and some mixing duties, I would certainly these headphones. data.text: Reviewed in the United States on March 7, 2018

I'm on my second pair now. I am a budding musician and part of what I do is singing so when I need to learn vocals for a song I need to be able to properly hear the vocals. These headphones let me do just that. They pick up soaring high notes and deep bass-y notes without putting too much emphasis on one or the other and without getting tinny with higher frequencies. The only reason my last pair wore is because the cord developed a short near the tip due to excessive movement (before that I had left them in one place, left them plugged in, and hung them on a hook when not in use and they lasted for well over a year). I love these headphones!Edit: Quick update, two years later and these headphones are still going strong! They really are great for the price. The bass notes come through clear without overpowering the music and the high notes are clear as well without being tinny. Where these headphones really shine is for music that puts emphasis on vocals or for listening to podcasts as the mids are extremely clear. These are also comfortable to wear for long periods of time due to the plush padding on the ear cups. Still highly recommended and still loving these headphones!Edit 2: It's now been 4 years and these headphones are still going strong! Still no complaints, except that they seem to be discontinuing this model (the MH320s)! I'll be sure to take care and look after mine as I'm still loving the quality.
